{"id": "60c439bd4f10440cb19b34abfcf74d26", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 06:43:06", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "Selected Action: Action 1.  \nReasoning: After several productive turns of discussion, our team has converged on a conceptually clear, methodologically tractable, and scientifically significant research direction: using local correlation analysis of counterfactual examples to disentangle syntactic influences from distributional biases in nationality-related name effects. The proposal is grounded in mechanistic interpretability and fairness-aware NLP, with a well-defined approach—leveraging controlled name substitutions, pseudo-name controls, and layer-wise representational analysis (e.g., RSA, CKA)—to move beyond aggregate bias detection toward causal diagnosis.\n\nWe now have a solid framework that includes:\n- A testable hypothesis (syntactic vs. distributional origins of model behavior shifts),\n- Concrete methodologies (counterfactual probing, local correlation analysis),\n- Control conditions to isolate variables (phonotactically matched pseudo-names, syntactically scrambled names),\n- Clear implications for intervention strategies based on findings,\n- And a feasible pilot plan using BERT-family models and existing benchmarks like WinoBias.\n\nWhile further discussion could refine details—such as multilingual extensions or specific layer-targeting protocols—the core idea is robust and sufficiently de-risked to proceed. Confirming the topic now enables us to advance to implementation, data collection, and experimentation without unnecessary delay. Early commitment also facilitates resource allocation,分工 planning, and alignment with related work in interpretability and fairness.\n\nTherefore, I believe we are ready to select this research topic and begin formalizing it into a study design.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[95mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
